segments.text: I was born in Beeville, Texas, February the 18th, 1913.
Yes, sir.
Could you tell us a little bit about your early life in Beeville, possibly a little bit about your father and mother, their names?
My father was Frederick William Heldenfels.
He was an A&M graduate of 1909.
My mother was Alice Cullen from Austin.
I went into B-Ville and did my school in B-Ville.
I actually started in Rockport in 1919.
Eric had discharged the school in Rockport, so I moved back to B-Ville and did all of my elementary and high school education in B-Ville.
When did you graduate from high school?
I graduated from high school in 1931.
And then you went to A&M in 1931?
I went to A&M in September 1931.
Why did you go to A&M?
What was your reason for going?
Well, I guess you might say I was from an A&M family.
My father was with A&M.
His brothers were at A&M.
My mother's brothers went to A&M.
I had an older brother at A&M.
and I actually gave no other schooling consideration.
I see.
What line of business was your father in?
My father at that time was in construction business.
So he had an engineering degree from 8 to 9?
No, he was a graduate architect student in the lumber business, had a lumber yard and an architect.
World War I, you got a contract to build ships for the government.
They moved to Rockport and opened up the shipyard.
And after the war, the government at that time were not able to pay off all the debts to the shipyards, so they gave the contractors all of the supplies
the materials that were left and the property and so forth as part payment.
And from that, he went into the construction business and marine construction to start.
In Rockport.
Rockport.
I see.
So then, could you tell us a little bit about your first impressions of the A&M campus when you started as a freshman?
Well, of course when I started freshman, my first assignment was in the tents.
I lived in tents that they had at that time between the railroad station up, I believe it's Puryear Law Hall, and then they had the tents.
And my first semester I was in tents, and then from there I moved into the new odometry building at that time at Walton Hall.
Could you tell us a little bit about your life in the tents?
Well, they're a little bit hard to remember.
Of course, we got out of them before there was really any cold weather.
I can't remember whether we carried wood or coal.
I think it was coal that we burned in our stove.
How many men to attend?
Four, if I recall correctly.
Do you remember anything about the furnishings, what they furnished the tents with?
No, outside just the cotton and so with those days we had wardrobe trunks.
We kept our clothes in wardrobe trunks.
I see.
Were there wooden floors in the tents?
Yes.
Any sides to them, wooden sides possibly?
I believe the sides were about two and a half, three feet.
I see.
There's some old pictures of them and I just don't really recall.
Yes sir, we have some.
Could you tell us what you remember about your freshman year?
No, not really too much.

I remember when I first went there, I got into, I ran into a hometown person who was, they were starting a Coastal Artillery at that time, and he'd been transferred in to start the new Corps, the Coastal Artillery,
He asked me to join the Co-Star Tailoring, and for that reason I got into the Co-Star Tailoring.
Were the upperclassmen very hard on you?
No, of course they had their hazing, but I think I enjoyed it more than I regretted it.
The military, the discipline of the military, the cadet corps I think probably did as much good for me as my whole education at A&M.
And what did you start out, what was your major?
I started out due to the fact that my father was an architect.
I started out as an architect, but then I, after the first year, I changed to finance.
And the reason I changed to finance at that time, my father became the owner of a bank.
In fact, Dr. Langford was my first professor up there in architecture.
Did you then go ahead and finish out in finance?
I finished out in finance, but I've never been into construction.
I worked in construction every summer, all through school, and from the day I got to college, I went into the construction field.
Could you possibly tell us about some of your more memorable experiences while you were at A&M?
good classes that you had, events that happened there that kicked off?
Well, I think that one of the professors that impressed me most was Dr. Crawford, mechanical engineer.
I really don't remember the instance that occurred, but for some reason he made an impression on me, and I've remembered him all the time since then, because he taught me.
in the old slide room, I forget what we called it then, the mechanical engineering slide room.
Professor Charles Denver Crawford is still living and is in good health.
He's quite a fine old gentleman.
Can you remember what social life went on there?
Well, there wasn't actually any much of what you might call social life.
You had to either catch a bus or a train into Brown.
It did have a motion picture.
I forget whether it was one day or two days or nights a week.
I don't really recall.
Do you remember where they held it?
It had a building there in the general vicinity where the All Faiths Chapel is now.
They had a theater there.
Could it possibly have been called Assembly Hall?
I believe it was just a movie theater.
I believe that's what it was for.
I see.
It was a building in that vicinity.
And of course you all had the football games to go to.
We had football games and we had a, I still remember, I believe it was Casey's that had a place in the old YMCA.
It was kind of a drug store or a kind of gathering point there.
That was, see when he was there the whole, the enrollment was around 2,500.
I believe in my class there were 527 or something like that that was started out that year.
Do you remember any of your fellow students?
Oh, very definitely.
In fact, my roommate, I roomed with the same person for four years, and unfortunately about six months ago he died, but I was associated with him ever since I was out of school.
What was his name?
Harold T. Bailey.
Mike Dillingham was another close friend of mine in school.
I still see him occasionally.
and I was on the Corps staff at that time.
We only had the one staff at the Corps.
I happened to be senior year.
I was on the Corps staff and most of the other people, persons on the staff went into professional
either military or the Navy, Marine Corps, and in fact there's quite a few of the boys that are my classmates who went into the Army or the Navy upon graduation to the Air Force.
Now this was during the Depression.
Can you remember how the Depression affected student life or affected
Well, no.
I do remember that most of the boys were real happy that they had a job offer in the $100 a month range when they got out.
It was about what I think $100 to $125 a month was about what we were getting.
I see.
Well, I was just curious to know if it made life on the campus a little tighter, if it was a little bit less for everybody?
Well, I really don't remember.
Of course, there wasn't much when you went there.
You paid your tuition, your books, and you really had not much to do away from it.
Most of the boys stayed on the campus weekend.
They didn't leave weekend, and that probably was maybe from depression or modes of travel, you might say, and of course at those times you were
An automobile on the campus was against the rules.
Some boys had them and kept them in brown, but there weren't many automobiles.
I have heard, do you remember any times when you might have seen hobos and bums riding
railroad through and stopping off at the school, possibly?
No, I don't.
Some that I've heard stories, some of the boys used to catch trains and ride.
I never did.
I always bought my ticket and didn't ride that way.
Did you ever have any major problems during your student days that you were able to?
I don't recall any major problems that I had.
What other professors besides Crawford?
Do you remember any others?
Yes, I remember the librarian.
I believe Dr. Mayo at that time.
I remember him, and I remembered Dr. Morgan, who was a math teacher I played.
I remember, of course, I remember Dr. Francis that was in the animal husbandry.
Veterinarian?
Yeah.
Do you remember anything about him?
Well, he was very colorful, sort of.
I've heard of this.
I don't remember the stories he used to tell, but he was a very, very colorful person, and it was a privilege to get to visit with him, or in groups where he used to talk.
When you were there, Bizzle was president of A&M.
Walton.
Walton was president of A&M, okay.
Excuse me.
Did you ever have any dealings with him?
I knew him and one of the reasons that I knew him, my older brother married a brown girl.
her father was in the extension service.
Do you remember what his name was?
Arms, RMS.
And he was a very close friend of Dr. Walter and through some association there I got to know him personally.
I see.
What type of man was he?
I thought he was very sort of quiet, sort of an easygoing sort of person as far as I could tell.
He wasn't
He wasn't high strung at all or anything like that.
He seemed like a very...
I remember Dr. Bolton too, the dean of engineering at that time.
Did you know him?
Knew him very well, yes.
What type of individual was he?
Well, he was...
I would say a little bit more of a stern person than Dr. Walton, but there was nothing out of it.
How did the students feel about President Walton?
Was he generally supported by the students?
As far as I know, I don't know of any, I don't recall of anybody being opposed to him in any way.
After you graduated from A&M, then where did you go?
Well, I came to Corpus Christi and I was joining my father in business.
My brother, who preceded me, graduated two years ahead of me, but also.
And from there, those days, we traveled around.
We had a job in
and say, Houston, well, I'd go and I'd live on the job.
And that's how I traveled around.
I mostly stayed on the coast where I was working.
And I came from Carpus.
And from Carpus, I went up into Missouria County.
Did you have a lot to learn about the construction business when you
Well, I had worked all the time.
The fact is, from the time I can remember, I had worked around construction and in construction, so it was nothing new to me.
Do you feel that your degree in finance helped you also?

Yes, I took, most of my electives I took in the field that I knew that I would be using, and I tried to more or less give my staff a rounded education, and if I had to do over again, if I knew I was going to do the same thing, I don't know if I'd change it at all.
So you felt very well prepared.
Yes, I did.
So after you came to Corpus, then you've really been here all along.
No, it was Carpus.
I left here in 1936 and went into Brazoria County and then from there into Houston and the Anuag, Beaumont area.
and back into El Campo and then about the time they started the WPA program and these counties had quite a bit of work and I came back into the Corpus area.
About that time they started the Naval Air Station.
And we had all the work that we could handle right here locally.
And I was here until I went in the Army, which I was called.
I had my commission, and I was called in the Army in September of 41.
What unit were you called into?
I was called into automatic weapons.
In what division?
Well, I wasn't in.
I was in a separate tag.
I see.
I see.
And I got out of the state of the service until February of 45.
Mm-hmm.
Where were you assigned most of the time?
Well, I was in Africa, Sicily, and then Sicily and Italy I was assigned to the support to the 1st Ranger Battalion, General Darby's.
Well, it was Colonel Darby's then.
All of my overseas was in Africa, Sicily, and Italy.
I see.
So then you saw quite a bit of combat.
Yes.
And then after you left the service in 45, did you come back to Corpus Christi?
I had my home.
In fact, when I was called into service, at that time I didn't own a home.
But when war was declared, I bought a home, put my family.
I had a wife and two children.
I see.
When were you married?
I was married in 1936.
Could you give me your wife's name?
Yes, her name was Hazel Norville.
See, from where?
Well, she was originally born in Russell County, but I met her in Missouri County when she was working for the county commissioner when I was up there doing work, and I met her in Missouri County.
And could you tell us a little bit about your life after the war?
You said you had a house.
Well, I moved back here and more or less took up just where I had left off.
My brothers and father were still running the business.
So I tried to catch up on any new methods or technology and so forth.
It's been the same ever since.
Now you were appointed to the board.
Yes.
By what government?
Price Daniels.
Price Daniels.
What year was this?
And you served how many years?
Twelve years.
Twelve years.
Could you tell us a little bit about your experiences on the board?

Yes, well actually I think that's probably one of the most rewarding experiences I've had and probably I was very fortunate to be on the board during the time that I was on because I think A&M had actually made the
great stride in both the growth student-wise and academic-wise, too.
It was a very, very rewarding experience, and I served as president of the board.
General Rudder there, president of the university, which was a very good, experiencing time.
Yes, I'll ask you in a minute about some impressions of General Rudder.
He's sort of a special interest of mine.
Was President Morgan, was he president when you came on the board?
No, Tom Harrington was president.
All right, so Morgan, let's see, Harrington.
Harrington was chancellor and Earl Rudder was...
I see.
Then Morgan and Hardy left by that time.
Yes.
I was wondering if possibly you knew some of the incidents.
I knew him.
You did.
But I've been pretty close to A&M ever since I've been out of A&M.
How did you stay active with A&M?
I'm curious.
Was it through the former students?
Mostly it was through athletics.
I've always
And then in the construction business, it seemed like we were always the one that they would call and want us to work with.
And so we were, I've always had several of the athletes working for me every summer.
I see, so you worked with many of the coaches then?

I worked, I knew practically every coach from time, well the same coach that I was in school with which I knew Coach Norton real well, he was still coach there after he got out of the Army, and then they hired
Stidler, who was from Carpus.
He was a high school coach here at Carpus for a while.
I knew Harry Stidler very well.
So if I was from Coach Norton, I've known all the coaches personally.
Ask a personal question.
You can answer it or not.
Who out of all that group impressed you the most?
Bear Bryant.
Bear Bryant.
I think that was a stupid question.
I can't.
I think he's just not even outstanding in anything.
He's just that type of person.
I see.
I think it's interesting that you've been able to work with the athletic department with so many people.
Were you saddened by Norton's leaving, or do you think it was timely that he left?
No, I knew Norton very well and I think it was time that he left.
I think everything had changed and he hadn't kept up with the changing times.
He was a personal friend of mine after he left as well as when he was there.
Can you think of any of the others that impressed you besides Brian?
He's such an overwhelming personality.

Well, I think that Gene's talent was probably, next to Brian, he was probably the most knowledgeable in football, although he had some traits that made it where he was in the head coach, whether it was age or what, but I believe that next to Brian, he probably, I thought, was more football, smarter coach.
and the rest of them.
Well, I think many people think that he is an excellent coach and probably will do very well at Dallas.
Well, he probably will.
I knew Ray Jarrett, of course his job was more or less
given to him, going on account of the Steidler situation.
He was there, just able to accept it, and he was probably a great assistant coach, but would not be a good head coach, the same as several of them, like Jim Meyer, probably.
Maybe the greatest assistant coach in the world, but just never could be a head coach.
Some people say that about Stallings.
Maybe time will tell.
Well, I don't know.
He certainly knows what it's about.
And have you worked with him in Ballard?
I've worked with him in Ballard.
I was on the group that interviewed him before they hired him, and I've worked very closely with him since he's been there.
I see.
Well, let's get back to your board experiences.
Can you think of some of the major occurrences that happened during your 12-year

Yes, of course the currency was when the compulsory military, it was dropped, and which was, but it had to, almost had to be on account of the way the Army and Air Corps changed their, where they could have a two-year program with the junior and senior year.
The coeducational
was brought about during the time of my board and I'm real happy with the way it's worked out.
I'm sure that was a tremendous struggle and a change too.
Well, it was.
Most all the board always felt like they should be.
coeducation on campus without housing.
That was the only real struggle with the board.
We didn't think anyone should be deprived of an education because they were female.
And if they lived in Bryan, but their parents were unable to afford to send them somewhere else, it felt like they shouldn't be able to do it.
get their education.
But the housing was the only thing that was really, to me, was a real, had a struggling decision.
Was the board pretty much divided on this issue?
Very definitely.
It had been divided on both co-education and housing.
I see.
Probably some very strong feelings about some former students.
I can understand their situation.
Yes, and we got lots of mail.
I'm sure you did.
It was probably both bad and good.
It wasn't bad, but we got to get.
Yes.
You say you have been pleased with the way coeducation has worked.
Yes, I am.
Of course, I'm not on the board now.
I don't like to dictate.
I hope that they don't go into where they start having the sorority.
We've never had the fraternities on the campus.
I hope they don't, but I imagine it will come in time.
Maybe, maybe not.
We hope not.
I think one thing that has been a problem is the growth of the campus.
They've grown so fast, too fast really.
Well, a thing that I also hope that they don't change the curriculum just to fit the female students.
I think it ain't even one of the things they ain't even always done.
It's taught a person a trade, a saleable trade, and it stayed away from the education just to be educated, you might say.
In other words, I felt like a person went to A&M, you could go hire him, he could do something.
And if they start changing the curriculum to meet, to satisfy the female student, then we may lose that.
I think we're losing off a lot over there.
Do you feel University of Boston should have a cut-off level that maybe we shouldn't grow to be, say, as large as the University of Boston?
Well, I think it all...
All universities should have a cutoff at one take.
In other words, there's a point when you once reach it that I think your efficiency just couldn't be there.
Now, it should be flexible.
I don't think you should say 20,000 and that's it.
I mean, it should be in a range of 19, 21.
Try to keep it in the way that you would do it by...
entrance examinators.
How you do it, that's always been the problem, where you cut it.
And they've
The entrance in the veterinary medicine has always been a real problem to the board.
There's so many little won't in there that say there's three or four hundred that are qualified.
They can pass any test you give them, but you can only take 128.
How do you do this?
And the board actually gets more harassment.
From that one thing, anything that I've ever had, more people would call you, including the governor.
And Dr. Price, I admire him for it.
He had his standards.
He stayed by it, and nobody could turn him.
He went by the rules and regulated his own, and I think he was good, but I just, I don't know how you

when you want to limit the enrollment to the to into a school but just how they are limited now by raising the entrance requirements and to have but I don't think that you can say you know you can take the one-fourths top fourths back I don't think you can do that.
What other problems can you find on the field?
Can you think of any others?
No, of course I, I wouldn't, I wouldn't think you could call it a problem.
Of course you always, you always had things like the, what did they call it then?
Well, it's not the union, but they have some society that they- AAUP, is that what it is?
American Association of University Professors.
They caused us a lot of bit of problem.
That is, a lot of headaches, you might say.
Was this over the Gibbs finding?
Over the Gibbs, or that type of thing.
to me, who had been dealing with either union, non-union, or construction work all my life, I didn't see the real threat that General Rudder and some of them, they felt like

they could leave a black mark on the university and you couldn't hire the type of professors you needed and after fooling with this several years and finally we just said well we can't satisfy them so forget them which we should have done to start with and so
That was the only real thing.
It was a tickly situation to deal with, not knowing what, thinking you might hurt the university, didn't want to hurt the university, tell you what you're doing was wrong.
Well, I would say time has proved you right, probably, because while we're still on their black list, if there is such a thing, it hasn't hurt us.
Well, most of the universities that were on the blacklist tried to get off and decided you can't get off and still run the university, so they're staying on.
The University of Texas was on it for years.
How do you believe General Rutter handled the university?
I think General Rutter was probably the best thing that ever happened to Texas A&M.
He was strictly an administrator.

I don't think he was an educator, but I think at A&M it was a period right then that the need and demand of his status, somebody that could just take the bull by the horn, you might say, and be an administrator and get enrolled in it.
He did.
Did you get to know him very well?
Oh, I knew him very well.
He stayed at my home many times.
I knew him well before he was president of the university.
I don't think any one man could have done any more than he did.
I think it ain't him as where he is today due to General Rudder.
Do you feel that he really managed to keep A&M quiet during the period of the 60s when other campuses were in turmoil and upheaval, were having their problems?
A&M, while they had problems, they never got out of hand.
Well, I think that he had quite a bit to do with it, but I think that your student body had more to do with it than he as an individual, because the type of students you have,
were not the type of students that you would find in these liberal arts colleges I referred to a while ago as people just being educated to be educated.
In other words, you're educated, but you can't do anything.
Well, that's the type that seemed to be caught in all the trouble, but the people they were learning, trying to learn something, the saleable trade, well, they didn't seem to have any trouble.
Did this ever come up at the board while this was going on and campuses in California were burning, so to speak?
Yes, it came up to the board.
In fact, there were several times that the board got notices that a certain agitator had caught a bus in a certain city and headed out that way and he'd pick up a brine.

alertness of the Rangers and so forth, they were picked up at the bus station and generally if they had a weapon or something, I don't know what they did, they had some reason to pick them up and search them.
So they were agitated, they tried to move into it, but I think the general rudder did see that the security was
We had during the board, we would get letters that there were going to be protests marched on the board meetings, but they never, none of them ever showed up.
This should have been gratifying to you anyway.
Yes, it was.
The student body did not become overly agitated.
You said you knew General Rudder well.
He was an administrator.
What kind of man was he personally out of the boardroom?
privately.
He was great company.
He loved me around.
He was a good conversationalist.
He was the type of person I could spend the day with.
I see.
Do you feel that
If A&M has any great weaknesses or if we've had any failures over the years while you were associated with the board, maybe a missed opportunity, something we could have done and didn't?
Oh, yes, you always, you'll have those, but I don't think that they had any missed opportunities that are actually set them back.
I think it was some opportunities that we probably could have taken and we probably may be a little bit further ahead, but I don't believe we had a missing opportunity to set us back.
Lots of times it's on whether you have the money to do this or not.
Of course, I think money has made a great difference to the school.
We're getting a little more now.
I think we were slow getting the psychotron just because
money situation.
We should have had it several years before we did, and I don't believe it set us back any.
We should have had the engineering building.
Well, the first board meeting I attended, the A&M, when I was sworn in, the board approved the plans of the engineering building.
What's now the Zachary Building.
Zachary Building.
And I was on the board 12 years.
I think it was built in my eleventh year.
So it's over for some things we drug our feet on or some things we shouldn't have drug our feet on and that's going to happen in anything like that.
Who out of all the members of the board that you served with impressed you?
Well, we had some very great men on the board.
Dr. Boyle was a fine man.
Sir Gardner Simon was a fine man.
L.F. Peterson, a very dedicated board member.
But you served with people that were corporate heads like Gardner Simon and Dr. Boyle.
They never missed your meeting.
They were just dedicated and it was really gratifying to serve on the board with that type of people.
What do you think were some of the greatest successes of the board?
Well, I don't really, I really don't know how to answer that question.
So weighty problems that you managed to finally solve where there might have been great division?
Well, I don't, I don't really believe we had those type of problems because actually the board
seem to be pretty well dedicated to trying to do the same thing.
There would be lots of arguments or conversation about how to do things, but generally they were all worked out.
I don't know of any problem we had that really confronted the court, where it might have divided the court.
You were on the board when Rutter was selected as president.
Yes.
Was he the first choice?
Oh, yes.
There never was any other thought about anybody else?
No.
Then you were on the board when they also selected Jack Williams.
Yes.
And he is an educator, probably, more than an administrator.
In fact, I'm the one who recommended Jack Williams.
Really, I talked to Earl Rudder prior to Earl's death.
In fact, it was back in about October.
At that time, Bulwer felt like General Rudder needed some help.
And we were wanting him to get somebody to work with him and to help him.
And we had

had talked about, he and I had talked about Jack Williams, and we had called him, telephoned, and he had had a meeting set up to talk to Dr. Williams about Bing coming in there as the body of Fred, but that meeting never took place.
stroke that he had.
Where did you know Dr. Williams from?
By reputation or personally?
No, I knew Dr. Williams, I was the president of the A&M board when he was over at the coordinating board.
And I got to, he spent quite a bit of time at A&M.
I'd see him up there quite often and he always told me he liked A&M, he liked to come there, this is where things are happening and this campus is so much different than the rest of it.
He liked me like he liked it.
He was making a talk
down in Carpus after General Rudder's death.

I called him on the phone and asked him if he would allow me to put his hat in the ring for the selection of the President and he said he just didn't know anything he liked better and so I did suggest him and we talked to quite a few people and but I think that

that everybody's happy I know that I'm just particularly there that he's there and I believe it that it was time and he moved in it's time that we needed an educator and we'd gone through the building stage to what Rudder had brought us and then an educator moving in is what we need an academic man there now.
And of course he's done an excellent job.
He's done an outstanding job.
Do you have anything coming on where the Corps of Cadets is going now?
It's considerably different than when you were in school there.
Well, of course it's different than when I was in school, but it's as large as all the school within it, and I think that if I was a youngster going to A&M today, I would get in the cadet corps.
I don't understand, of course I'm not that age anymore,
To me, everybody, well, cadet corps is still a symbol of A&M.
It's the image.
I know it's a discipline that some of them don't want, but to me, that discipline is just as much a part of education.
I hope it comes back.
I just do.
You know, next year we're going to have girls in the Corps.
Well, I think that's... My father always said that they ought to have a wax up there.
He was always for that.
So I think as long as they're going to have the girls or ladies in the services, I think they should have them in the Corps.
I don't know that they'll mix them.
I imagine they'll have their own...
Oh, yes.

I understand the way they're going to do it is they're going to have the first year their officers will be males who are in the Corps now, and then they'll turn loose on their own after they've got them indoctrinated into the ways and policies and traditions.
It should work out well.
Can you think of anything else off the board?
I don't want to miss anything, and yet, not having been there, I'm not sure what to ask.
Of course I was, I spent most of my time on the board as the chairman of the building committee and due to my experience, I'm sure that's the reason they selected me for, and I was
